[src:echo-framework/front-controller] The **front controller** software design pattern is listed in several pattern catalogs and is related to the design of web applications.
[src:echo-framework/front-controller] It is "a controller that handles all requests for a website," which is a useful structure for web application developers to achieve flexibility and reuse without code redundancy.
[src:echo-framework/front-controller] Front controllers are often used in web applications to implement workflows.
[src:echo-framework/front-controller] While not strictly required, it is much easier to control navigation across a set of related pages (for instance, multiple pages used in an online purchase) from a front controller than it is to assign individual pages responsibility for navigation.
[src:echo-framework/front-controller] The front controller may be implemented as a Java object, or as a script in a scripting language such as PHP, Raku, Python or Ruby that is called for every request of a web session.
[src:echo-framework/front-controller] This script would handle all tasks that are common to the application or the framework, such as session handling, caching and input filtering.
[src:echo-framework/front-controller] Based on the specific request, it would then instantiate further objects and call methods to handle the required tasks.
[src:echo-framework/front-controller] The alternative to a front controller is the usage of page controllers mapped to each site page or path.
[src:echo-framework/front-controller] Although this may cause each individual controller to contain duplicate code, the page-controller approach delivers a high degree of specialization.
[src:echo-framework/front-controller] Request processor: used for request processing and modifying or retrieving the appropriate model.
[src:echo-framework/front-controller] Flow manager: determines what will be shown on the next page.
[src:echo-framework/front-controller] There are three primary benefits associated with the front controller pattern.
[src:echo-framework/front-controller] The front controller pattern may incur performance issues because the single controller is performing a great deal of work, and handlers may introduce bottlenecks if they involve database or document queries.
[src:echo-framework/front-controller] The front controller approach is also more complex than that of page controllers.
[src:echo-framework/front-controller] The data for the application is best handled in a single location, obviating the need for duplicate data-retrieval code.
[src:echo-framework/front-controller] Different roles in the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern should be separated to increase testability, which is also true for the controller part in the MVC pattern.
[src:echo-framework/front-controller] The page-controller pattern is an alternative to the front controller approach in the MVC model.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] A third-party source-to-source compiler, GopherJS, transpiles Go to JavaScript for front-end web development.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go was designed at Google in 2007 to improve programming productivity in an era of multicore, networked machines and large codebases.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Its designers were primarily motivated by their shared dislike of C++.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go was publicly announced in November 2009, and version 1.0 was released in March 2012.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go is widely used in production at Google and in many other organizations and open-source projects.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] In retrospect the Go authors judged Go to be successful due to the overall engineering work around the language, including the runtime support for the language's concurrency feature.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The gopher mascot was introduced in 2009 for the open source launch of the language.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Renée French, who had designed the rabbit mascot for Plan 9, adapted the gopher from an earlier WFMU T-shirt design.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] In November 2016, the Go and Go Mono fonts were released by type designers Charles Bigelow and Kris Holmes specifically for use by the Go project.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go is a humanist sans-serif resembling Lucida Grande, and Go Mono is monospaced.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Both fonts adhere to the WGL4 character set and were designed to be legible with a large x-height and distinct letterforms.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Both Go and Go Mono adhere to the DIN 1450 standard by having a slashed zero, lowercase `i` with a tail, and an uppercase `I` with serifs.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] In April 2018, the original logo was redesigned by brand designer Adam Smith.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The new logo is a modern, stylized GO slanting right with trailing streamlines.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The lack of support for generic programming in initial versions of Go drew considerable criticism.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The designers expressed an openness to generic programming and noted that built-in functions *were* in fact type-generic, but are treated as special cases; Pike called this a weakness that might be changed at some point.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The Google team built at least one compiler for an experimental Go dialect with generics, but did not release it.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] In August 2018, the Go principal contributors published draft designs for generic programming and error handling and asked users to submit feedback.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] However, the error handling proposal was eventually abandoned.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] In June 2020, a new draft design document was published that would add the necessary syntax to Go for declaring generic functions and types.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] A code translation tool, *go2go*, was provided to allow users to try the new syntax, along with a generics-enabled version of the online Go Playground.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Generics were finally added to Go in version 1.18 on March 15, 2022.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go 1 guarantees compatibility for the language specification and major parts of the standard library.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] All versions up through the current Go 1.26 release have maintained this promise.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go uses a `go1.[major].[patch]` versioning format, such as `go1.26.0` and each major Go release is supported until there are two newer major releases.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Unlike most software, Go calls the second number in a version the major, i.e., in `go1.26.0` the `26` is the major version.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] This is because Go plans to never reach 2.0, prioritizing backwards compatibility over potential breaking changes.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go is influenced by C (especially the Plan 9 dialect), but with an emphasis on greater simplicity and safety.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go's syntax includes changes from C aimed at keeping code concise and readable.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] A combined declaration/initialization operator was introduced that allows the programmer to write `i := 3` or `s := "Hello, world!"`, without specifying the types of variables used.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] This contrasts with C's `int i = 3;` and `char *s = "Hello, world!";` (though since C23 type inference has been supported using `auto`, like C++).
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go also removes the requirement to use parentheses in `if` statement conditions.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Semicolons still terminate statements; but are implicit when the end of a line occurs.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Methods may return multiple values, and returning a `result, err` pair is the conventional way a method indicates an error to its caller in Go.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go adds literal syntaxes for initializing struct parameters by name and for initializing maps and slices.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] As an alternative to C's three-statement `for` loop, Go's `range` expressions allow concise iteration over arrays, slices, strings, maps, and channels.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go has a number of built-in types, including numeric ones (`byte`, `int64`, `float32`, etc.), Booleans, and byte strings (`string`).
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Strings are immutable; built-in operators and keywords (rather than functions) provide concatenation, comparison, and UTF-8 encoding/decoding.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Record types can be defined with the `struct` keyword.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Note that `byte` is an alias for `uint8` and `rune` is an alias for `int32`.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] For each type `T` and each non-negative integer constant `n`, there is an array type denoted `[n]T`; arrays of differing lengths are thus of different types.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Dynamic arrays are available as "slices", denoted `[]T` for some type `T` (compare to other languages like C/C++ and Java, where instead the arrays are denoted `T[]`) These have a length and a *capacity* specifying when new memory needs to be allocated to expand the array.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Several slices may share their underlying memory.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] For a pair of types `K`, `V`, the type `map[K]V` is the type mapping type-`K` keys to type-`V` values, which can be thought of as equivalent to `Map<K, V>` in other languages.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The Go Programming Language specification does not give any performance guarantees or implementation requirements for map types, though it is usually implemented as a hash table (equivalent to `HashMap<K, V>` in other languages).
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Hash tables are built into the language, with special syntax and built-in functions.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] `chan T` is a *channel* that allows sending values of type `T` between concurrent Go processes.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Aside from its support for interfaces, Go's type system is nominal: the `type` keyword can be used to define a new *named type*, which is distinct from other named types that have the same layout (in the case of a `struct`, the same members in the same order).
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Some conversions between types (e.g., between the various integer types) are pre-defined and adding a new type may define additional conversions, but conversions between named types must always be invoked explicitly.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] With this type definition, `ipv4addr(x)` interprets the `uint32` value `x` as an IP address.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Simply assigning `x` to a variable of type `ipv4addr` is a type error.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Any named type has a method set associated with it.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Due to nominal typing, this method definition adds a method to `ipv4addr`, but not on `uint32`.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] While methods have special definition and call syntax, there is no distinct method type.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go provides two features that replace class inheritance.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The first is *embedding*, which can be viewed as an automated form of composition.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The second are its *interfaces*, which provides runtime polymorphism.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Interfaces are a class of types and provide a limited form of structural typing in the otherwise nominal type system of Go.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] An object which is of an interface type is also of another type, much like C++ objects being simultaneously of a base and derived class.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The design of Go interfaces was inspired by protocols from the Smalltalk programming language.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Multiple sources use the term duck typing when describing Go interfaces.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Although the term duck typing is not precisely defined and therefore not wrong, it usually implies that type conformance is not statically checked.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Because conformance to a Go interface is checked statically by the Go compiler (except when performing a type assertion), the Go authors prefer the term *structural typing*.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The definition of an interface type lists required methods by name and type.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Any object of type T for which functions exist matching all the required methods of interface type I is an object of type I as well.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The definition of type T need not (and cannot) identify type I.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] then both a `Square` and a `Circle` are implicitly a `Shape` and can be assigned to a `Shape`-typed variable.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] In formal language, Go's interface system provides structural rather than nominal typing.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Interfaces can embed other interfaces with the effect of creating a combined interface that is satisfied by exactly the types that implement the embedded interface and any methods that the newly defined interface adds.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The Go standard library uses interfaces to provide genericity in several places, including the input/output system that is based on the concepts of `Reader` and `Writer`.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Besides calling methods via interfaces, Go allows converting interface values to other types with a run-time type check.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The *empty interface* `interface{}` is an important base case because it can refer to an item of *any* concrete type.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] It is similar to the `Object` class in Java or C# or `void*` in C or `Any` in C++ and Rust and is satisfied by any type, including built-in types like `int`.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Code using the empty interface cannot simply call methods (or built-in operators) on the referred-to object, but it can store the `interface{}` value, try to convert it to a more useful type via a type assertion or type switch, or inspect it with Go's `reflect` package.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Because `interface{}` can refer to any value, it is a limited way to escape the restrictions of static typing, like `void*` in C but with additional run-time type checks.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The `interface{}` type can be used to model structured data of any arbitrary schema in Go, such as JSON or YAML data, by representing it as a `map[string]interface{}` (map of string to empty interface).
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] This recursively describes data in the form of a dictionary with string keys and values of any type.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Interface values are implemented using pointer to data and a second pointer to run-time type information.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Like some other types implemented using pointers in Go, interface values are `nil` if uninitialized.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Since version 1.18, Go supports generic code using parameterized types.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Functions and types now have the ability to be generic using type parameters.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] These type parameters are specified within square brackets, right after the function or type name.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The compiler transforms the generic function or type into non-generic by substituting *type arguments* for the type parameters provided, either explicitly by the user or type inference by the compiler.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] This transformation process is referred to as type instantiation.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Interfaces now can define a set of types (known as type set) using `|` (Union) operator, as well as a set of methods.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] These changes were made to support type constraints in generics code.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] For a generic function or type, a constraint can be thought of as the type of the type argument: a meta-type.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] This new `~T` syntax will be the first use of `~` as a token in Go.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] `~T` means the set of all types whose underlying type is `T`.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go uses the `iota` identifier to create enumerated constants.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] In Go's package system, each package has a path (e.g., `"compress/bzip2"` or `"golang.org/x/net/html"`) and a name (e.g., `bzip2` or `html`).
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] By default other packages' definitions must *always* be prefixed with the other package's name.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] However the name used can be changed from the package name, and if imported as `_`, then no package prefix is required.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Only the *capitalized* names from other packages are accessible: `io.Reader` is public but `bzip2.reader` is not.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The Go language has built-in facilities, as well as library support, for writing concurrent programs.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The runtime is asynchronous: program execution that performs, for example, a network read will be suspended until data is available to process, allowing other parts of the program to perform other work.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] This is built into the runtime and does not require any changes in program code.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The go runtime also automatically schedules concurrent operations (goroutines) across multiple CPUs; this can achieve parallelism for a properly written program.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The primary concurrency construct is the *goroutine*, a type of green thread.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] A function call prefixed with the `go` keyword starts a function in a new goroutine.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] While a standard library package featuring most of the classical concurrency control structures (mutex locks, etc.) is available, idiomatic concurrent programs instead prefer *channels*, which send messages between goroutines.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Optional buffers store messages in FIFO order and allow sending goroutines to proceed before their messages are received.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Channels are typed, so that a channel of type `chan T` can only be used to transfer messages of type `T`.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Special syntax is used to operate on them; `<-ch` is an expression that causes the executing goroutine to block until a value comes in over the channel `ch`, while `ch <- x` sends the value `x` (possibly blocking until another goroutine receives the value).
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The built-in `switch`-like `select` statement can be used to implement non-blocking communication on multiple channels; see below for an example.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go has a memory model describing how goroutines must use channels or other operations to safely share data.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The existence of channels does not by itself set Go apart from actor model-style concurrent languages like Erlang, where messages are addressed directly to actors (corresponding to goroutines).
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] In the actor model, channels are themselves actors, therefore addressing a channel just means to address an actor.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The actor style can be simulated in Go by maintaining a one-to-one correspondence between goroutines and channels, but the language allows multiple goroutines to share a channel or a single goroutine to send and receive on multiple channels.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] From these tools one can build concurrent constructs like worker pools, pipelines (in which, say, a file is decompressed and parsed as it downloads), background calls with timeout, "fan-out" parallel calls to a set of services, and others.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Channels have also found uses further from the usual notion of interprocess communication, like serving as a concurrency-safe list of recycled buffers, implementing coroutines (which helped inspire the name *goroutine*), and implementing iterators.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Concurrency-related structural conventions of Go (channels and alternative channel inputs) are derived from Tony Hoare's communicating sequential processes model.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Unlike previous concurrent programming languages such as Occam or Limbo (a language on which Go co-designer Rob Pike worked), Go does not provide any built-in notion of safe or verifiable concurrency.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] While the communicating-processes model is favored in Go, it is not the only one: all goroutines in a program share a single address space.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] This means that mutable objects and pointers can be shared between goroutines; see § Lack of data race safety, below.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Although Go's concurrency features are not aimed primarily at parallel processing, they can be used to program shared-memory multi-processor machines.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Various studies have been done into the effectiveness of this approach.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] One of these studies compared the size (in lines of code) and speed of programs written by a seasoned programmer not familiar with the language and corrections to these programs by a Go expert (from Google's development team), doing the same for Chapel, Cilk and Intel TBB.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The study found that the non-expert tended to write divide-and-conquer algorithms with one `go` statement per recursion, while the expert wrote distribute-work-synchronize programs using one goroutine per processor core.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The expert's programs were usually faster, but also longer.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go's approach to concurrency can be summarized as "don't communicate by sharing memory; share memory by communicating".
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] There are no restrictions on how goroutines access shared data, making data races possible.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Specifically, unless a program explicitly synchronizes via channels or other means, writes from one goroutine might be partly, entirely, or not at all visible to another, often with no guarantees about ordering of writes.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Furthermore, Go's *internal data structures* like interface values, slice headers, hash tables, and string headers are not immune to data races, so type and memory safety can be violated in multithreaded programs that modify shared instances of those types without synchronization.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Instead of language support, safe concurrent programming thus relies on conventions; for example, Chisnall recommends an idiom called "aliases xor mutable", meaning that passing a mutable value (or pointer) over a channel signals a transfer of ownership over the value to its receiver.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The gc toolchain has an optional data race detector that can check for unsynchronized access to shared memory during runtime since version 1.1, additionally a best-effort race detector is also included by default since version 1.6 of the gc runtime for access to the `map` data type.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The linker in the gc toolchain creates statically linked binaries by default; therefore all Go binaries include the Go runtime.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go deliberately omits certain features common in other languages, including (implementation) inheritance, assertions, pointer arithmetic, implicit type conversions, untagged unions, and tagged unions.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The designers added only those facilities that all three agreed on.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Of the omitted language features, the designers explicitly argue against assertions and pointer arithmetic, while defending the choice to omit type inheritance as giving a more useful language, encouraging instead the use of interfaces to achieve dynamic dispatch and composition to reuse code.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Exception handling was initially omitted in Go due to lack of a "design that gives value proportionate to the complexity".
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] An exception-like `panic`/`recover` mechanism that avoids the usual `try-catch` control structure was proposed and released in the March 30, 2010 snapshot.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The Go authors advise using it for unrecoverable errors such as those that should halt an entire program or server request, or as a shortcut to propagate errors up the stack within a package.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Across package boundaries, Go includes a canonical error type, and multi-value returns using this type are the standard idiom.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] It also includes profiling and debugging support, fuzzing capabilities to detect bugs, runtime instrumentation (for example, to track garbage collection pauses), and a data race detector.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Another tool maintained by the Go team but is not included in Go distributions is `gopls`, a language server that provides IDE features such as intelligent code completion to Language Server Protocol compatible editors.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] An ecosystem of third-party tools adds to the standard distribution, such as `gocode`, which enables code autocompletion in many text editors, `goimports`, which automatically adds/removes package imports as needed, and `errcheck`, which detects code that might unintentionally ignore errors.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] where "fmt" is the package for *formatted I/O*, similar to C's <stdio.h> or C++ <print>.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The following simple program demonstrates Go's concurrency features to implement an asynchronous program.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] It launches two lightweight threads ("goroutines"): one waits for the user to type some text, while the other implements a timeout.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The select statement waits for either of these goroutines to send a message to the main routine, and acts on the first message to arrive (example adapted from David Chisnall's book).
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The testing package provides support for automated testing of go packages.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] It is possible to run tests in parallel.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The net/http package provides support for creating web applications.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] This example would show "Hello world!" when localhost:8080 is visited.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go has found widespread adoption in various domains due to its robust standard library and ease of use.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The interface system, and the deliberate omission of inheritance, were praised by Michele Simionato, who likened these characteristics to those of Standard ML, calling it "a shame that no popular language has followed [this] particular route".
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] By June 2015, its ranking had dropped to below 50th in the index, placing it lower than COBOL and Fortran.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] But as of January 2017, its ranking had surged to 13th, indicating significant growth in popularity and adoption.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] Go was again awarded TIOBE Programming Language of the Year in 2016.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] The evaluation got a rebuttal from the Go development team.
[src:echo-framework/go-programming-language] On November 10, 2009, the day of the general release of the language, Francis McCabe, developer of the Go! programming language (note the exclamation point), requested a name change of Google's language to prevent confusion with his language, which he had spent 10 years developing.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:echo-framework/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] A **web server** is computer software that accepts requests via HTTP (the network protocol created to distribute web content) or its secure variant HTTPS.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] A user agent, commonly a web browser or web crawler, initiates communication by making a request for a web page or other resource using HTTP, and the server responds with the content of that resource or an error message.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] A web server can also accept and store resources sent from the user agent if configured to do so.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] The hardware used to run a web server can vary according to the volume of requests that it needs to handle.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] At the low end of the range are embedded systems, such as a router that runs a small web server as its configuration interface.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] A high-traffic Internet website might handle requests with hundreds of servers that run on racks of high-speed computers.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] A resource sent from a web server can be a pre-existing file (static content) available to the web server, or it can be generated at the time of the request (dynamic content) by another program that communicates with the server software.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] The former usually can be served faster and can be more easily cached for repeated requests, while the latter supports a broader range of applications.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Technologies such as REST and SOAP, which use HTTP as a basis for general computer-to-computer communication, as well as support for WebDAV extensions, have extended the application of web servers well beyond their original purpose of serving human-readable pages.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In March 1989, Sir Tim Berners-Lee proposed a new project to his employer CERN, with the goal of easing the exchange of information between scientists by using a hypertext system.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] The proposal titled *"HyperText and CERN"*, asked for comments and it was read by several people.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In October 1990 the proposal was reformulated and enriched (having as co-author Robert Cailliau), and finally, it was approved.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Those early browsers retrieved web pages written in a simple early form of HTML from web servers using a new basic communication protocol that was named HTTP 0.9.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In August 1991 Tim Berners-Lee announced the *birth of WWW technology* and encouraged scientists to adopt and develop it.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Soon after, those programs, along with their source code, were made available to people interested in their usage.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Although the source code was not formally licensed or placed in the public domain, CERN informally allowed users and developers to experiment and further develop on top of them.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Berners-Lee started promoting the adoption and the usage of those programs along with their porting to other operating systems.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In December 1991, the **first web server outside Europe** was installed at SLAC (U.S.A.).
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] This was a very important event because it started trans-continental web communications between web browsers and web servers.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In 1991–1993, CERN web server program continued to be actively developed by the www group, meanwhile, thanks to the availability of its source code and the public specifications of the HTTP protocol, many other implementations of web servers started to be developed.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In April 1993, CERN issued a public official statement stating that the three components of Web software (the basic line-mode client, the web server and the library of common code), along with their source code, were put in the public domain.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] This statement freed web server developers from any possible legal issue about the development of *derivative work* based on that source code (a threat that in practice never existed).
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1994, the most notable among new web servers was NCSA httpd which ran on a variety of Unix-based OSs and could serve *dynamically generated content* by implementing the `POST` HTTP method and the CGI to communicate with external programs.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] These capabilities, along with the multimedia features of NCSA's Mosaic browser (also able to manage HTML FORMs in order to send data to a web server) highlighted the potential of web technology for publishing and distributed computing applications.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1995 those patches were all applied to the last release of NCSA source code and, after several tests, the Apache HTTP server project was started.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] At the end of 1994, a new commercial web server, named Netsite, was released with specific features.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] It was the first one of many other similar products that were developed first by Netscape, then also by Sun Microsystems, and finally by Oracle Corporation.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In mid-1995, the first version of IIS was released by Microsoft for Windows NT OS.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] This marked the entry, in the field of World Wide Web technologies, of a commercial developer and vendor that has played and still is playing a key role on both sides (client and server) of the web.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In the second half of 1995, CERN and NCSA web servers started to decline (in global percentage usage) because of the widespread adoption of new web servers which had a much faster development cycle along with more features, more fixes applied, and more performances than the previous ones.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] At the end of 1996, there were already over fifty known, different web-server-software programs that were available to everybody who wanted to own an Internet domain name or to host websites.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Many of them lived only shortly and were replaced by other web servers.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] The publication of RFCs about protocol versions HTTP/1.0 (1996) and HTTP/1.1 (1997, 1999), forced most web servers to comply (not always completely) with those standards.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] The use of TCP/IP persistent connections (HTTP/1.1) required web servers both to increase the maximum number of concurrent connections allowed and to improve their level of scalability.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Between 1996 and 1999, Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's IIS emerged among the leading commercial options whereas among the freely available and open-source programs Apache HTTP Server held the lead as the preferred server (because of its reliability and its many features).
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In those years there was also another commercial web server called Zeus (*now discontinued*) that was known as one of the fastest and most scalable web servers available on market, at least till the first decade of 2000s, despite its low percentage of usage.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Apache resulted in the most used web server from mid-1996 to the end of 2015 when, after a few years of decline, it was surpassed initially by IIS and then by Nginx.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Afterward IIS dropped to much lower percentages of usage than Apache (see also market share).
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] From 2005–2006, Apache started to improve its speed and its scalability level by introducing new performance features (e.g., event MPM and new content cache).
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] A few years after 2000 started, not only other commercial and highly competitive web servers (e.g., LiteSpeed) but also many other open-source programs such as Hiawatha, Cherokee HTTP server, Lighttpd, Nginx and other derived and related products also available with commercial support emerged.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Within a year, these changes, on average, nearly tripled the maximum number of persistent connections that web servers had to manage.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In 2015, RFCs published new protocol version [HTTP/2], and as the implementation of new specifications was not trivial at all, a **dilemma arose among developers of less popular web servers** (e.g., with a percentage of usage lower than 1% ..
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] 2%), about adding or not adding support for that new protocol version.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In 2020–2021 the HTTP/2 dynamics about its implementation (by top web servers and popular web browsers) were partly replicated after the publication of advanced drafts of future RFC about HTTP/3 protocol.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] The following technical overview should be considered only as an attempt to give a few very *limited examples* about *some* features that may be implemented in a web server and *some* of the tasks that it may perform in order to have a sufficiently wide scenario about the topic.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] A **web server program** plays the role of a server in a client–server model by implementing one or more versions of HTTP protocol, often including the HTTPS secure variant and other features and extensions that are considered useful for its planned usage.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Although web server programs differ in how they are implemented, most of them offer the following common features.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] These are **basic features** that most web servers usually have.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] A few other more **advanced** and popular **features** (*only a very short selection*) are the following ones.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Once an HTTP request message has been decoded and verified, its values can be used to determine whether that request can be satisfied or not.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] This requires many other steps, including **security checks**.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] The term *URL normalization* refers to the process of modifying and standardizing a URL in a consistent manner.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] There are several types of normalization that may be performed, including the conversion of the scheme and host to lowercase.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Among the most important normalizations are the removal of "." and ".." path segments and adding trailing slashes to a non-empty path component.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] One or more configuration files of web server may specify the mapping of parts of **URL path** (e.g., initial parts of file path, filename extension and other path components) to a specific URL handler (file, directory, external program or internal module).
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to translate an URL path (all or part of it), that refers to a physical file system path, to an absolute path under the target website's root directory.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Website's root directory may be specified by a configuration file or by some internal rule of the web server by using the name of the website which is the host part of the URL found in HTTP client request.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] The web server appends the path found in requested URL (HTTP request message) and appends it to the path of the (Host) website root directory.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] On an Apache server, this is commonly `/home/www/website` (on Unix machines, usually it is: `/var/www/website`).
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] See the following examples of how it may result.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] The web server then reads the file, if it exists, and sends a response to the client's web browser.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the file and contain the file itself or an error message will return saying that the file does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the directory (list of contained subdirectories and files) or an error message will return saying that the directory does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] For a *dynamic request* the URL path specified by the client should refer to an existing external program (usually an executable file with a CGI) used by the web server to generate dynamic content.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] The web server executes that program, passing in the path-info and the query string `action=view&orderby=thread&date=2021-10-15` so that the program has the info it needs to run.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] (In this case, it will return an HTML document containing a view of forum entries ordered by thread from October 15, 2021).
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In addition to this, the web server reads data sent from the external program and resends that data to the client that made the request.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Once a request has been read, interpreted, and verified, it has to be managed depending on its method, its URL, and its parameters, which may include values of HTTP headers.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] That kind of content is called *static* because usually it is not changed by the web server when it is sent to clients and because it remains the same until it is modified (file modification) by some program.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Response of static file content can be sped up by a **file cache**.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Most used names for static index files are: `index.html`, `index.htm` and `Default.htm`.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] If a web server program receives a client request message with an URL whose path matches the file name of an existing *file* and that file is accessible by web server program and its attributes match internal rules of web server program, then web server program can send that file to client.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Usually, for security reasons, most web server programs are pre-configured to serve only regular files or to avoid to use *special file types* like device files, along with symbolic links or hard links to them.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] The aim is to avoid undesirable side effects when serving static web resources.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] If a web server program is capable of **serving dynamic content** and it has been configured to do so, then it is able to communicate with the proper internal module or external program (associated with the requested URL path) in order to pass to it the parameters of the client request.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] After that, the web server program reads from it its data response (that it has generated, often on the fly) and then it resends it to the client program who made the request.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In order to be able to communicate with its internal modules or external programs, a web server program must have implemented one or more of the many available **gateway interfaces** (see also Web Server Gateway Interfaces used for dynamic content).
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] The three **standard** and historical **gateway interfaces** are the following ones.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] An external CGI program is run by web server program for each dynamic request, then web server program reads from it the generated data response and then resends it to client.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] An external FastCGI program (it usually is a process) is started once by web server program or by some other program or process and then it waits for a network connection which is established permanently by web server; through that connection are sent the request parameters and read data responses.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] A web server program may be capable to manage the dynamic generation (on the fly) of a **directory index list** of files and sub-directories.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] If it cannot be generated an error is returned.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Usage of dynamically generated *directory listings* is usually avoided or limited to a few selected directories of a website because that generation takes much more OS resources than sending a static index page.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] The main usage of *directory listings* is to allow the download of files (usually when their names, sizes, modification date-times or file attributes may change randomly and frequently) *as they are, without requiring to provide further information to requesting user*.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In practice whenever there is content that may vary, depending on one or more parameters contained in client request or in configuration settings, then, usually, it is generated dynamically.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to send response messages as replies to client request messages.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] An error response message may be sent because a request message could not be successfully read or decoded or analyzed or executed.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] NOTE: the following sections are reported only as examples to help to understand what a web server, more or less, does; these sections are by any means neither exhaustive nor complete.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] When an error response or message is received by a client browser, then if it is related to the main user request (e.g., an URL of a web resource such as a web page) then usually that error message is shown in some browser window or message.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Example 1: a URL path points to a **directory** name but it does not have a final slash '/' so web server sends a redirect to client in order to instruct it to redo the request with the fixed path name.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Example 2: a whole set of documents has been **moved inside website** in order to reorganize their file system paths.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Example 3: a whole set of documents has been **moved to a new website** and now it is mandatory to use secure HTTPS connections to access them.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Above examples are only a few of the possible kind of redirections.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] A web server program is able to reply to a valid client request message with a successful message, optionally containing requested **web resource data**.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] If web resource data is sent back to client, then it can be **static content** or **dynamic content** depending on how it has been retrieved (from a file or from the output of some program or module).
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In order to speed up web server responses by lowering average HTTP response times and hardware resources used, many popular web servers implement one or more content caches, each one specialized in a content category.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In practice, nowadays, many web server programs include their own *userland* **file cache**, tailored for a web server usage and using their specific implementation and parameters.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] The wide spread adoption of RAID and fast solid-state drives (storage hardware with very high I/O speed) has slightly reduced but of course not eliminated the advantage of having a file cache incorporated in a web server.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Dynamic content, output by an internal module or an external program, may not always change very frequently (given a unique URL with keys or parameters) and so, maybe for a while (e.g., from one second to several hours or more), the resulting output can be cached in RAM or even on a fast disk.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Anyway, in most cases those kind of caches are implemented by external servers (e.g., reverse proxy) or by storing dynamic data output in separate computers, managed by specific applications (e.g., memcached), in order to not compete for hardware resources (CPU, RAM, disks) with web servers.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] A web server software can be either incorporated into the OS and executed in kernel space, or it can be executed in user space (like other regular applications).
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Web servers that run in user-mode have to ask the system for permission to use more memory or more CPU resources.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Not only do these requests to the kernel take time, but they might not always be satisfied because the system reserves resources for its own usage and has the responsibility to share hardware resources with all the other running applications.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Executing in user mode can also mean using more buffer or data copies (between user-space and kernel-space) which can lead to a decrease in the performance of a user-mode web server.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Nowadays almost all web server software is executed in user mode (because many of the aforementioned small disadvantages have been overcome by faster hardware, new OS versions, much faster OS system calls and new optimized web server software).
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] See also comparison of web server software to discover which of them run in kernel mode or in user mode (also referred as kernel space or user space).
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In other words, a **web server should always be very responsive**, even under high load of web traffic, in order to keep **total user's wait** (sum of browser time + network time + **web server response time**) for a response **as low as possible**.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Among the operating conditions, the **number** (1 ..
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] *n*) of **concurrent client connections** used during a test is an important parameter because it allows to correlate the **concurrency level** supported by web server with results of the tested performance metrics.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] ... used to implement a web server program, **can bias a lot the performances** and in particular the **scalability level** that can be achieved under **heavy load** or when using high end hardware (many CPUs, disks and lots of RAM).
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] In practice some web server software models may require more OS resources (specially more CPUs and more RAM) than others to be able to work well and so to achieve target performances.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p01] Performances of a web server are typically benchmarked by using one or more of the available automated load testing tools.
[src:echo-framework/web-server-p02] When a web server is near to or over its load limits, it gets **overloaded** and so it may become **unresponsive**.
